# TypeScript / React Development Standards

Apply these conventions when generating or modifying TypeScript or React code.

## Types

Always use explicit types — avoid `any`. Prefer interfaces for object shapes, type aliases for unions/intersections.

```typescript
// ✅ Good
interface Resource {
    id: string;
    name: string;
    provider: 'aws' | 'azure' | 'gcp';
    createdAt: string;
}

// ❌ Bad
const resource: any = { ... };
```

## Functions and components

Use `const` with arrow functions for React components. Destructure props with an interface:

```tsx
interface ResourceCardProps {
    resource: Resource;
    onDelete: (id: string) => void;
    className?: string;
}

export const ResourceCard: React.FC<ResourceCardProps> = ({
    resource,
    onDelete,
    className = '',
}) => {
    return (
        <div className={`resource-card ${className}`}>
            <h3>{resource.name}</h3>
        </div>
    );
};
```

## Hooks

Extract reusable state logic into custom hooks. Handle loading and error states explicitly:

```typescript
export const useResources = () => {
    const [resources, setResources] = useState<Resource[]>([]);
    const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);
    const [error, setError] = useState<string | null>(null);

    const fetchResources = useCallback(async () => {
        setLoading(true);
        setError(null);
        try {
            const data = await resourceService.list();
            setResources(data);
        } catch (err) {
            setError(err instanceof Error ? err.message : 'Failed to fetch');
        } finally {
            setLoading(false);
        }
    }, []);

    return { resources, loading, error, fetchResources };
};
```

## Naming conventions

- Components and types: `PascalCase` — `ResourceCard`, `UserService`
- Functions and variables: `camelCase` — `getUserById`, `isLoading`
- Constants: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` — `API_BASE_URL`, `MAX_RETRIES`
- Files: `kebab-case` — `resource-card.tsx`, `use-resources.ts`

## Error handling

Always handle promise rejections. Use `try/catch` in async functions:

```typescript
async function fetchUser(id: string): Promise<User> {
    if (!id) throw new Error('User ID is required');
    const response = await api.get(`/users/${id}`);
    return response.data;
}
```

## Imports

Organize imports: external libraries → internal modules → relative imports. Use barrel exports (`index.ts`) for directories.

## Linting and formatting

- `eslint` with `prettier` for style enforcement
- `eslint --fix` and `prettier --write` before committing
- `tsc --noEmit` to check types without building
